subject: Manager: Add read routines for ManagerDiagnosticData, read CPU stats
commitMessage:
Manager: Add read routines for ManagerDiagnosticData, read CPU stats

Reading diagnostic data involves the following 4 steps:
1. Find the BMC inventory item DBus object.
2. Find the Association edges going out from the object.
3. Find the objects reachable from the edges (the objects are usually
   the utilization sensors published by phosphor-health-monitor.)
4. Get the diagnostic data from those objects.

Add the BMC's CPU utilization.
The utilization will be provided via utilization sensors serviced by
phosphor-health-monitoring with the change in
https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/phosphor-health-monitor/+/45835

The Redfish resource populated will be the ManagerDiagnosticData that
will enter Redfish 2021 Release 4. The properties used are:
ManagerDiagnosticData.ProcessorStatistics.KernelPercent, and
ManagerDiagnosticData.ProcessorStatistics.UserPercent.

Tested: Set up phosphor-health-monitor, added an EntityManager config
for the BMC inventory, ran `curl` and saw CPU usage of the BMC:

curl -k -u root:0penBmc -X GET
https://localhost:18080/redfish/v1/Managers/bmc/ManagerDiagnosticData
{
  "@odata.id": "/redfish/v1/Managers/bmc/ManagerDiagnosticData",
  "@odata.type": "#ManagerDiagnosticData.ManagerDiagnosticData",
  "ProcessorStatistics": {
    "KernelPercent": 5.077919416730467,
    "UserPercent": 2.932867307589972
  }
}

Signed-off-by: Sui Chen <suichen@google.com>
Change-Id: Ib77f343f881432e5a057e546f43faf0a80d80b9b

Sorry for the code not building, I fixed the build errors and tested in local CI. I was too anxious to get some progress after a very long hiatus and was a bit overwhelmed by having to address (the discussion involved in) both bmcweb and phosphor-health-monitor simultaneously (for the sensor names on DBus) for this to work at all.

What I was asking is I would like to use this change to restart the discussion on what are good names for the utilization sensors' DBus objects. Previously there was a concern that "CPU_Kernel" and "CPU_User" show up in the WebUI and confuse the user as they look like host CPU usage and someone mentioned prefixing the objects with "BMC", but if I remember correctly there were concerns over prefixing too. With contradicting comments on prefixing the sensor names with "BMC" I'm not sure this is what I can solve alone, so I'd rather post this change with the original bad names and get this discussed.

Regarding the handler code in the change, hopefully I have made it simple and clear enough this time.

The naming issue would affect not just the BMC CPU metric, but other metrics as well. So I would appreciate it if there is one unified voice on the naming. What names would you suggest?

> What I was asking is I would like to use this change to restart the discussion on what are good names for the utilization sensors' DBus objects. Previously there was a concern that "CPU_Kernel" and "CPU_User" show up in the WebUI and confuse the user as they look like host CPU usage and someone mentioned prefixing the objects with "BMC", but if I remember correctly there were concerns over prefixing too. With contradicting comments on prefixing the sensor names with "BMC" I'm not sure this is what I can solve alone, so I'd rather post this change with the original bad names and get this discussed.

This exact concern is why we generally use associations for this kind of thing.  As a matter of extension, lets say we had the host CPU usage available as well, given that people might want to pick their sensor name, how would we differentiate between the BMC CPU usage and the host CPU usage?

> 
> Regarding the handler code in the change, hopefully I have made it simple and clear enough this time.
> 
> The naming issue would affect not just the BMC CPU metric, but other metrics as well. So I would appreciate it if there is one unified voice on the naming. What names would you suggest?

I don't really think we should use names at all.  In general, Name should ideally be user-configurable and user-facing;  We've been burned before by hardcoding a specific name, then a system needed to pick a different name, because name is user-facing.  We need a generic way to describe "this is the CPU usage for this component" which in general we use associations, this would just be a specific association.
